processSpecContent extracts &lt;ref spec="…"&gt; edges from a spec's innerxml using a strict regex grammar: the spec attribute must use double quotes and appear as the first attribute, in either self-closing form (&lt;ref spec="X" /&gt;) or paired form (&lt;ref spec="X"&gt;label&lt;/ref&gt;). It returns the canonical content (each ref replaced by its label text, or removed entirely for self-closing refs) plus the list of referenced spec IDs in source order. Duplicate (from, to) pairs within the same spec are deduped at the scanner level so validation never sees them. Malformed &lt;ref&gt; tags (typos like &lt;red spec="X"&gt; or missing spec attribute) cause a scan error; refs to nonexistent spec IDs do NOT error here — they surface as TodoBrokenRef drift items. See principles.specs_are_truth.